1
00:00:01,980 --> 00:00:04,860
Instructor: When we work with orders in any website

2
00:00:04,860 --> 00:00:07,110
we typically have two tables.

3
00:00:07,110 --> 00:00:11,610
One is order header and one is order details.

4
00:00:11,610 --> 00:00:15,210
Order header will have all the information about order

5
00:00:15,210 --> 00:00:17,460
like where the order is being shipped,

6
00:00:17,460 --> 00:00:21,000
what is the payment status, what was the order date,

7
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:22,980
what was the payment ID

8
00:00:22,980 --> 00:00:26,610
what is the tracking information and much more.

9
00:00:26,610 --> 00:00:30,270
Order details will have all the details about that order

10
00:00:30,270 --> 00:00:32,850
like what are the items in this order

11
00:00:32,850 --> 00:00:37,320
and what is the count of each item and so on.

12
00:00:37,320 --> 00:00:40,320
So we have to create both of these tables

13
00:00:40,320 --> 00:00:43,830
and let me switch back, stop the application,

14
00:00:43,830 --> 00:00:46,140
close all the tabs here

15
00:00:46,140 --> 00:00:48,813
and we will go to the models project.

16
00:00:49,890 --> 00:00:53,970
Right click here, add a new model.

17
00:00:53,970 --> 00:00:58,290
First one here will be order header.cs

18
00:00:58,290 --> 00:01:01,353
and the next one will be order details.

19
00:01:07,336 --> 00:01:12,003
We will make both of them public class here and perfect.

20
00:01:13,290 --> 00:01:17,550
First, we'll work on all the properties in order header.

21
00:01:17,550 --> 00:01:19,680
ID is pretty straightforward.

22
00:01:19,680 --> 00:01:23,100
Every order needs a unique ID.

23
00:01:23,100 --> 00:01:28,100
Then each order will belong to a user and user ID is a grid.

24
00:01:28,290 --> 00:01:33,000
So we will say application user ID which will be a string

25
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:38,000
and that will be foreign key to the application user table.

26
00:01:38,010 --> 00:01:40,590
So we will have to add the foreign key

27
00:01:40,590 --> 00:01:43,290
and where we have the navigation property

28
00:01:43,290 --> 00:01:46,170
make sure to add validate never.

29
00:01:46,170 --> 00:01:48,330
We do not want to validate that

30
00:01:48,330 --> 00:01:52,383
when we will be creating or updating any order header.

31
00:01:53,834 --> 00:01:56,160
Next property here will be a date time

32
00:01:56,160 --> 00:01:58,890
and that will be order date

33
00:01:58,890 --> 00:02:01,350
and when an order will be shipped,

34
00:02:01,350 --> 00:02:04,170
we will also have another date time

35
00:02:04,170 --> 00:02:06,213
which will be order shipped.

36
00:02:07,080 --> 00:02:12,080
So shipping date and we will have a double

37
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:14,673
which will be order total.

38
00:02:18,210 --> 00:02:19,950
Perfect, that looks good.

39
00:02:19,950 --> 00:02:23,910
Then for each order we have an order status.

40
00:02:23,910 --> 00:02:25,890
On top of order status,

41
00:02:25,890 --> 00:02:29,700
I will also be adding something called as payment status.

42
00:02:29,700 --> 00:02:34,115
That will give us an idea of what happens with payment

43
00:02:34,115 --> 00:02:37,440
of an order, whether it is pending, it is completed

44
00:02:37,440 --> 00:02:39,930
or it is a delayed payment.

45
00:02:39,930 --> 00:02:42,030
Once the order is shipped

46
00:02:42,030 --> 00:02:44,220
then we want to add the tracking number

47
00:02:44,220 --> 00:02:47,883
and the carrier information so they can track the order.

48
00:02:49,020 --> 00:02:50,550
Lastly, if you remember

49
00:02:50,550 --> 00:02:53,880
for company user we will give them net 30 days

50
00:02:53,880 --> 00:02:57,810
to make payment after the order has been placed.

51
00:02:57,810 --> 00:03:00,870
So we can also track what is the payment date

52
00:03:00,870 --> 00:03:03,003
and by when the payment is due.

53
00:03:03,930 --> 00:03:04,920
Now the due date

54
00:03:04,920 --> 00:03:07,560
I want that to be a date field only,

55
00:03:07,560 --> 00:03:09,750
because of that with EF Core

56
00:03:09,750 --> 00:03:12,540
we have a special feature date only

57
00:03:12,540 --> 00:03:14,070
and that will be converted

58
00:03:14,070 --> 00:03:18,963
to a date only field when EF Core generates the SQL query.

59
00:03:19,950 --> 00:03:23,640
So we have date only and time only if that is needed

60
00:03:23,640 --> 00:03:26,700
but we do not need time only for this case.

61
00:03:26,700 --> 00:03:29,490
We will be using date only.

62
00:03:29,490 --> 00:03:32,820
Finally, when we work with payments using credit card

63
00:03:32,820 --> 00:03:37,050
and Stripe, we will be getting a unique ID from Stripe

64
00:03:37,050 --> 00:03:39,930
which will be payment intent ID

65
00:03:39,930 --> 00:03:43,110
that will uniquely identify each payment

66
00:03:43,110 --> 00:03:45,630
that has been done for an order

67
00:03:45,630 --> 00:03:48,093
and we will save that in the database.

68
00:03:49,110 --> 00:03:52,710
Other properties that we want to add here are basically

69
00:03:52,710 --> 00:03:57,710
name of the person and phone number and street address.

70
00:03:57,840 --> 00:04:00,090
These are the same properties that we added

71
00:04:00,090 --> 00:04:01,950
in the view as well.

72
00:04:01,950 --> 00:04:05,370
So we have phone number, street address, city,

73
00:04:05,370 --> 00:04:08,013
state, postal code and name.

74
00:04:08,910 --> 00:04:13,140
With that configured the order header looks in great shape.

75
00:04:13,140 --> 00:04:16,589
We have added quite a few properties there.

76
00:04:16,589 --> 00:04:20,310
Next, let me work on order details here.

77
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:24,490
There also we will need ID for the order details

78
00:04:25,620 --> 00:04:28,980
but along with that we need the order ID

79
00:04:28,980 --> 00:04:33,030
and that order ID will be the order header ID.

80
00:04:33,030 --> 00:04:37,473
So if you want to be explicit you can say order header ID.

81
00:04:38,310 --> 00:04:41,190
Now this order header ID will be a foreign key

82
00:04:41,190 --> 00:04:42,750
to the order header.

83
00:04:42,750 --> 00:04:46,920
So make sure to add the foreign key and order header.

84
00:04:46,920 --> 00:04:50,943
We will add the validate never with the navigation property.

85
00:04:51,780 --> 00:04:55,620
Next property that we want here is the product ID

86
00:04:55,620 --> 00:04:58,050
and then we will have navigation property

87
00:04:58,050 --> 00:05:00,060
for product as well.

88
00:05:00,060 --> 00:05:03,540
So let me add the navigation property for product

89
00:05:03,540 --> 00:05:07,830
and then for each product what is the count or quantity?

90
00:05:07,830 --> 00:05:12,150
So we will add a count and I will also be logging

91
00:05:12,150 --> 00:05:13,383
what is the price.

92
00:05:14,220 --> 00:05:17,610
So we will have double and price here.

93
00:05:17,610 --> 00:05:20,310
And the reason I am logging price is

94
00:05:20,310 --> 00:05:22,500
if you examine the product here

95
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:26,610
it can happen that in future that price can be updated

96
00:05:26,610 --> 00:05:28,500
but when we place an order

97
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:32,130
we want to log that, hey, this is the price user got

98
00:05:32,130 --> 00:05:35,610
for the order and that should never change.

99
00:05:35,610 --> 00:05:39,723
So it makes sense to add price inside the order details.

100
00:05:41,040 --> 00:05:43,890
With that configured, I believe order details

101
00:05:43,890 --> 00:05:47,070
and order header looks good for now.

102
